\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Negative AGN migration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Evgeni Grishin
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
evgeni.grishin@monash.edu
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Intro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gravitational interactions between massive bodies in their nascient discs
 lead to net energy change and migration, and were stidues extensively in
 planetary science 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see review by"
key "Paardekooper_review"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the standard picture, the gravitational interaction raises two spiral
 density waves excited at various resonances (corotation, inner and outer
 Lindblad, ref), and their imbalance leads to net migration.
 Low mass object don't form a gap and migrate as type I migrate, where the
 net torque is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{I}\propto m_{p}^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the mass of the planet.
 Massive planets open a gap and their migration rate is independent of the
 mass of the planet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The type I torque is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma_{0}\sim\frac{q^{2}}{h^{2}}\Sigma r^{4}\Omega^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q=m/M$
\end_inset

 is the mass ratio, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=H/r$
\end_inset

 is the aspect ratio and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=(GM/r^{3})^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 is the Keplerian frequency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The migration timescale is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{0}=\frac{L}{2\Gamma_{0}}=\frac{mr^{2}\Omega}{2\Gamma_{0}}=\frac{1}{2\Omega}\frac{h^{2}}{q}\frac{M}{\Sigma r^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

 For type II, the timescale is the viscous timescale of the disc, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\nu}=\Omega^{-1}\times(\alpha h^{2})^{-1}.$
\end_inset

 This could be fast, unless the planet is massive than the disc, than it
 will slow down by a factor is 
\begin_inset Formula $m/4\pi\Sigma r^{2}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
What is the gap opening criterion?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Naively, at some critical mass ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{c},$
\end_inset

 the viscous torques will not be able to replenish the annular gap cleared
 out by the gravitational torques.
 Comparing the timescales, the transition is expected to occur in 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{h^{2}}{q}\frac{M}{\Sigma r^{2}}\le\frac{1}{\alpha h^{2}}\left(1+\frac{m}{4\pi\Sigma r^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $m\gg\Sigma r^{2}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}M^{2}/m\le m/4\pi\alpha h^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $q\ge\sqrt{4\pi\alpha}h^{2}\approx3\cdot10^{-4}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\le\Sigma r^{2}$
\end_inset

 but still type II dominated, we have (
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma r^{2}/M)\ge q\ge\frac{M}{\Sigma r^{2}}\alpha h^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 The latter has a very narrow range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is really not the case.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "crida2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 realised that additional pressure torque are important and derived a semi-empir
ical criterion: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{h}{q^{1/3}}+50\frac{\alpha h^{2}}{q}\lesssim1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently the gap opening criterion had been revised to (Kanagawa+2015)
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q\ge5\sqrt{\alpha h^{5}}\approx10^{-4}\alpha_{0.01}^{1/2}h_{0.04}^{5/2},
\]

\end_inset

 so we're back to 
\begin_inset Formula $q\propto\sqrt{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, although the scaling with 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 varies again.
 The extra 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 power of h could be from 3D analysis (Tanaka+2002).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
How migration can be reversed?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Accretion may result in feedback and imbalance the vicinity of the planet.
 For gas accretion, it is expected to accelerate the migration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lega14"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but accretion of pebbles could stall, or even reverse it 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "b-l15"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Local simulations had shown that the heating torque can be important for
 wide range of configurations in accretion discs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hankla2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "masset17"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studies analytically the responce of a disc to a thermal torque.
 The additional variables are the thermal conductivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 which enter into the heat transport part of the diffusion equation: The
 heat flux is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F}_{H}=-\chi\rho\nabla(e/\rho)$
\end_inset

 (eq.
 4), where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the energy density and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the gas density.
 Without and sources, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}e=\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\boldsymbol{F}_{H}$
\end_inset

, which looks like diffusion if the density gradient is small.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other length scale is the heat deposition scale is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\sqrt{\chi/q\Omega\gamma}$
\end_inset

 (eq.
 120) where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the adiabatic index, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the Keplerian frequency and 
\begin_inset Formula $q=-d\ln\Omega/d\ln r=3/2$
\end_inset

 is the shear strength.
 Usually, the heat deposition scale is small compared to the scale height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda/H\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Radiative diffusion is usually the main source of diffesion, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi=16(\gamma-1)\sigma_{{\rm SB}}T^{3}/3\rho^{2}\kappa(\mathcal{R}/\mu)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the gas constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the mean molar mass.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eq.
 146 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "masset17"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the total thermal torque reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma_{{\rm th}}^{{\rm tot}}=1.61\frac{\gamma-1}{\gamma}\eta\frac{H^{2}}{\lambda r}\left(\frac{L}{L_{c}}-1\right)\Gamma_{0}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{0}=\Sigma r^{4}\Omega^{2}(m/M_{\star})^{2}(H/r)^{-3}$
\end_inset

 is the nominal type I torque (eq.
 134), 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}=4\pi Gm\chi\rho_{0}/\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the heat release from the planet (eq.
 132), 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the luminosity and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\alpha/3+(\beta+3)/6$
\end_inset

 is related to the gradients of the surface density (
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\propto r^{-\alpha}$
\end_inset

) and the temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T\propto r^{-\beta}$
\end_inset

) gradients, and usually is of order unity.
 It is valid for planets of mass less than 
\begin_inset Formula $m<m_{c}=\chi c_{s}/G,$
\end_inset

 othewise the heat is deposited beyond the Bondi radius and the effect is
 greatly reduced.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fro19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also found that the eccentricity and inclination grow if 
\begin_inset Formula $L/L_{c}>1$
\end_inset

 or dampen when 
\begin_inset Formula $L/L_{c}<1$
\end_inset

 exponentially.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
AGNS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Migration traps had been involved in AGN discs as fruitful locations for
 BH accumulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bellovary16"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hankla2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 looked on both AGNS and protoplanetary discs: corotation torque is complex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They investigate the validity of the liner approach of Masset and directly
 apply to AGN disc.
 For the conductivity we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\chi & =\frac{16\gamma(\gamma-1)\sigma T^{4}}{3\kappa\rho_{0}^{2}H^{2}\Omega^{2}}=\frac{6\gamma(\gamma-1)}{\kappa\rho_{0}^{2}}\tau\alpha\Omega\Sigma\\
 & =12\pi\gamma(\gamma-1)\alpha H^{2}\Omega\sim0.167\frac{\alpha}{0.01}H^{2}\Omega
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 checking length scales: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\lambda}{H}=\sqrt{24\pi^{3}\gamma(\gamma-1)\alpha}=1.8
\]

\end_inset

 not that great..
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ratio between the torques is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Gamma_{{\rm heat}}}{\Gamma_{0}}=0.07\frac{c}{v_{k}}\frac{1}{\alpha^{3/2}\tau}
\]

\end_inset

so for optically thick, but not too thick (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\lesssim2000),$
\end_inset

 the thermal torque can possible dominate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "li2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 numerically studies the Gruzinov negative DFs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Kaaz+2022 studies jet launching mechanisms from magnetised gas in BHL accretion.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=5/3$
\end_inset

 launches nice jets and reduces (or even) reversed the drag force, while
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=4/3$
\end_inset

 doesn't really do much.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "tagawa2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studies the role of mechanical feedback of rapidly accreting BHs.
 Winds can be launched for super-eddington accretion, but it doesn't hamper
 the flow too much.
 Jet feedback mechanism (JFM) causes episodic accretion and reduces rates
 by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $10-100.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derdzinski+2000 discuss the birth and evolution of stars from gravitationally-un
stable AGN discs.
 The IMF is probably top heavy.
 The initial stars are small, below 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm \odot}}$
\end_inset

, but could rapidly accrete and grow.
\end_layout

